Communicated by:
Mary Marshall
<mjm2020@googlemail.com>

[Sequence data: https://github.com/inrb-drc/ebola-equateur-2020/tree/master/data
Figures: https://github.com/inrb-drc/ebola-equateur-2020/tree/master/docs

This interesting finding does not distinguish between transmission of the 2018 genotype from a persistently infected person or a new spillover event from a sylvatic source. The slow rate of mutation leading to only 10 mutations in this new strain compared to the 2018 strain suggests persistence but doesn't answer the question whether this is persistence in bats or another animal or humans. An experimental study on Marburg virus suggests it persisted within experimentally infected _Rousettus aegyptiacus_ bats for 7 months (Schuh AJ et al. Nat. Commun. 2017; 8: 14446) but it could equally have been a persistently infected person who initiated a new transmission chain, perhaps though sexual transmission. - Mod.LK


